  "rationale": "Out-of-fold, AUROC declines monotonically across the age gradient (<40 0.751 \u2192 40-60 0.698 \u2192 60-80 0.659 \u2192 80+ 0.623). The material signal is this CUMULATIVE age gradient, not an 80+ cliff: the adjacent 80+ vs 60-80 step is sub-threshold (\u0394=-0.036 CI [-0.055, -0.018] \u2014 statistically significant but |\u0394| \u2264 0.05), while the cumulative multi-band gaps clear the bar (80+ vs 40-60 \u0394=-0.075 CI [-0.097, -0.052], material; 80+ vs <40 \u0394=-0.128 CI [-0.159, -0.096], material). The age finding is REAL and best described as a gradient in rank-separability with age \u2014 not a discontinuity at 80+; the plausible mechanism is case mix (elderly risk distributions are compressed, so ranking is intrinsically harder). On calibration, 80+ OOF ECE is 0.006 \u2014 far below the 0.05 per-subgroup bar, so 80+ is merely less rank-separable, still well-calibrated. Caveat: this ECE is measured on calibrated OOF scores the committed isotonic map was itself fit on (so it is mildly optimistic FOR THE CALIBRATOR), but that small monotone-map optimism cannot lift 0.006 across the 0.05 bar \u2014 the 'well-calibrated, not miscalibrated' conclusion is robust to the caveat.",
